---
/**
 * Write detail — "Dropping Security Code Because the Threat Didn't Exist".
 * Bespoke per-topic body. Different structure from the first write on purpose:
 * a threat-model framing → a callout on the actual input path → the principle.
 * Grounded in the homepage summary; deepen with real specifics anytime.
 */
import WriteLayout from '../../layouts/WriteLayout.astro';
---

<WriteLayout
  slug="dropping-security-code"
  title="Dropping Security Code Because the Threat Didn't Exist"
  dek="Defensive code that protected against nothing."
  description="An engineering-judgment case study: cutting SQL-escaping defensive code after finding every input came from typed config models, not users — the threat surface did not exist."
>
  <p class="lead" data-reveal>
    There was a block of SQL-escaping code wearing the costume of caution. It looked
    responsible — the kind of thing nobody removes because removing security code
    feels like the wrong direction. So I did the unglamorous part first: I traced
    where its inputs actually came from.
  </p>

  <div class="frame" data-reveal>
    <span class="frame__label">The input path</span>
    <p class="frame__text">
      Every value reaching that query originated in typed configuration models —
      not user input, not a request body, nothing crossing a trust boundary. The
      strings the escaping defended against could never arrive.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p data-reveal>
    A defense is only worth its complexity if there's a threat for it to absorb.
    Here the threat surface didn't exist. The escaping code wasn't a safety margin;
    it was a misread of where danger lived. Keeping it would have signalled a
    protection that wasn't real — the worst kind, because it invites you to relax.
  </p>

  <p class="principle" data-reveal>
    So it went. The principle I carry out of it: security code earns its keep by
    matching a real threat model, not by looking defensive. Model the input path
    before you harden it — and when the threat isn't there, the most secure move
    is to delete the code that pretended it was.
  </p>
</WriteLayout>

<style>
  .lead {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: var(--t-sm); line-height: var(--lh-snug);
    color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
  }
  p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: var(--t-lead); line-height: var(--lh-body);
    color: var(--ink-dim); max-width: 66ch;
  }
  p + p { margin-top: 1.2rem; }

  /* Framed callout — the finding that flips the piece, in a glass plate. */
  .frame {
    margin: clamp(2rem, 5vh, 3rem) 0;
    padding: clamp(1.2rem, 3.5vw, 1.8rem);
    border: 1px solid var(--glass-edge); border-radius: 14px;
    background: var(--glass-sheen), linear-gradient(var(--glass-dim), var(--glass-dim));
    backdrop-filter: blur(var(--glass-blur)) saturate(1.05);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(var(--glass-blur)) saturate(1.05);
  }
  .frame__label {
    display: block; font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--t-micro); letter-spacing: 0.22em; text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--gold); margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
  }
  .frame__text {
    font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 500;
    font-size: var(--t-sm); line-height: var(--lh-snug); color: var(--ink);
  }
  .principle { color: var(--ink); margin-top: clamp(1.6rem, 4vh, 2.4rem); }
</style>
